# Parallel analysis to determine how many component will be required

cor(Cruiseship_isi$Length,pc_cruiseship$scores)
##            RC1        RC2
## [1,] 0.9397714 0.06988624

Interpretation:

The column labeled RC1, and RC2 contains the component loadings which are correlations of the observed variables with in principle component

The column labeled h2 contains the component communalities- the amount of variance in each variable explained by the components

The column labeled u2 contains the component uniqueness - the amount of variance not accounted by the components

The row labeled SS loadings contains the eighenvalues associated with the components, the eighen values are the standardized variance associated with a particular component

The row labeled Proportion Var represents the amount of variance accounted for by each component

The first component accounts for 75 % of the variance in the Cruiseship data,where as the second component accounts for 16%

Together the two components accounts for 91% of the variance.

The two components together account for 27% of the variance in the YearBlt variable, 11 % of variance in Length, 10 % OF variance in PasssSpcR and 8 % of Outcab in the cruise ship data

.

\[ Tonnage= -2.67 + 8.17 * PassSpcR + 5.7 * Crew + 2.3 * Cabins + 3.5 * Length \]

From the above equation we can say that there is an expected increase of 8.17 percent of total Tonnage of a ship if PassengerSpc gets increased an unit it will also be increased at 5.7 percent when its Crew increase a unit, it will be increased at 2.3 when cabin is increased a unit

Applying Unsupervised K-means algorithm

# Initialize total within sum of squares error: wss
wss <- 0

# Look over 1 to 15 possible clusters
for (i in 1:15) {
  # Fit the model: km.out
  km.out <- kmeans(Cruiseship_isi[,-c(1:2)], centers = i, nstart = 20, iter.max = 50)
  # Save the within cluster sum of squares
  wss[i] <- km.out$tot.withinss
}



# Produce a scree plot
plot(1:15, wss, type = "b", 
     xlab = "Number of Clusters", 
     ylab = "Within groups sum of squares")

# Select number of clusters (2, 3, 4 probably OK)
k <- 2


# Build model with k clusters: km.out
km.out <- kmeans(Cruiseship_isi[-c(1:2)], centers = k, nstart = 20, iter.max = 50)

ggplot(Cruiseship_isi,aes(Length,passngrs,col=as.factor(km.out$cluster))) + geom_point() + facet_wrap(~Line) +labs(title="k-means clustering of CruiseShip with 2 clusters")

Formulation Hypothesis on Cars data

CASE 1:

Null hypothesis: The avg. Highway Mpg of a vehicle is the same for RATIO AND TURBO vehicles

Alternate hypothesis: The avg. Highway Mpg of Turbo vechicle is higher than the RATIO ones

Auto_hyp1 <- AutoPriceRating_isi %>% select(Aspiration,`Highway-mpg`) %>% mutate(Aspiration=factor(Aspiration))

#Generate 1000 differences in means via randomization

null_distribution_auto_model <- Auto_hyp1 %>%
  specify(`Highway-mpg` ~ Aspiration) %>%
  hypothesize(null = "independence") %>%
  generate(reps = 1000, type = "permute") %>% 
  calculate(stat = "diff in means", order = c("std", "turbo"))

#  Calulcate diff in observed means
obs_stat_auto_model <- Auto_hyp1  %>% 
  group_by(Aspiration) %>%
  summarize(mean = mean(`Highway-mpg`)) %>%
  summarize(obs_stat = diff(mean)) %>%
  pull(obs_stat)

# P value

null_distribution_auto_model %>%
  filter(stat>obs_stat_auto_model) %>%
  summarize(p_val = n() / 1000) %>%
  pull()
## [1] 1
# Visualization

plot_model <- null_distribution_auto_model %>% 
  visualize()

plot_model + geom_vline(xintercept = obs_stat_auto_model, col = "red", size = 1) + geom_vline(color = "red", xintercept = -obs_stat_auto_model)

P value caluclated is greater than significance level 0.05, hence we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

CASE 2:

Null hypothesis: The avg city mpg is the same across all the cylinders type cars

Alternate hypothesis: The avg city mpg of a differs between at least one pair of cylinder

# Transformation

Auto_hyp2 <- AutoPriceRating_isi %>% select(`Num-of-cylinders`, `City-mpg`) %>% mutate(`Num-of-cylinders`=as.factor(`Num-of-cylinders`))

# Applyting anova

Auto_aov <- aov(`City-mpg` ~ `Num-of-cylinders`, data=Auto_hyp2) %>% tidy()

SST <- Auto_aov[[1,3]] + Auto_aov[[2,3]]

Auto_aov_percentage_of_explained_var <- Auto_aov[[1,3]] / SST

# Summary

print(Auto_aov)
##                 term  df    sumsq   meansq statistic      p.value
## 1 `Num-of-cylinders`   6 3472.757 578.7928  21.79403 1.299979e-19
## 2          Residuals 198 5258.365  26.5574        NA           NA
print(Auto_aov_percentage_of_explained_var)
## [1] 0.3977446

P value caluclated is higher than significance level 0.05, hence we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

Interpretation

Overall accuracy is calculated at just over 87%, the classifier seems to be doing a pretty reasonable job of classifying items.

Sensitivity and specificity respectively help us measure the performance of the classifier in correctly predicting the actual class of an item and not predicting the class of an item that is of a different class; it measures true positive and true negative performance.

From the above data we can see that our classifier correctly identified class Meeting 78% of the time. That is, when we should have predicted class Meeting we did. Further, when we shouldnt have predicted class Meeting we didnt for 95%.

Class Meeting has a positive predictive value of over 93%: despite our classifier only being able to positively identify objects 78% of the time theres a 93% chance that, when it does, such a classification is correct.
